"'''Problem'''" is a song by the American singer [[Ariana Grande]], featuring the Australian rapper [[Iggy Azalea]]. It was written by both alongside [[Savan Kotecha]], [[Ilya Salmanzadeh|Ilya]] and [[Max Martin]], being produced by the latter two with [[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]], with [[Carolina Liar|Peter Carlsson]] serving as a vocal producer. The song was released by [[Republic Records]] on April 28, 2014, as the [[lead single]] from Grande's second studio album ''[[My Everything (Ariana Grande album)|My Everything]]'' (2014). "Problem" is an [[uptempo]] [[dance-pop]] song with influences of [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] music, which comprises a melody based on [[drums]], [[saxophone]] loops, and [[trumpets]]. The chorus features uncredited background vocals from American hip hop artist [[Big Sean]]. Lyrically, Grande has stated that the song is about "the feeling of being absolutely terrified to re-approach a relationship that's gone sour – but you want to more than anything."

The song debuted at number three on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] selling 438,000 copies in its first week on sale, earning Grande her biggest digital song sales week ever. The song later peaked at number two, surpassing "[[The Way (Ariana Grande song)|The Way]]" as her highest-charting single in the United States at the time. It also became Azalea's second-highest charting single in the US, after her own single "[[Fancy (Iggy Azalea song)|Fancy]]". "Problem" remained in the top ten of the Hot 100 for the first sixteen weeks of its chart run, making its number three debut on May 7, 2014 and dropping out of the top ten on August 27, 2014. It topped the US [[Mainstream Top 40]] and [[Rhythmic (chart)|Rhythmic]] charts. Internationally, the single debuted at the top of the charts in Ireland, New Zealand, Scotland and the United Kingdom, while peaking within the top ten of the charts in most other territories, including Australia, Canada, Sweden, Denmark, and Greece. "Problem" became the first song to top the UK Singles chart based on both sales and streaming.

To promote the song, Grande performed it first at the [[2014 Radio Disney Music Awards]], followed by the [[2014 iHeartRadio Music Awards]], on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' and at the [[2014 Billboard Music Awards]]. The song's accompanying [[music video]] was directed by Nev Todorovic and premiered on [[Vevo]] on May 30, 2014. It won "Best Pop Video" at the [[2014 MTV Video Music Awards]] and has been viewed more than 1.1 billion times. The song itself won "Best Song" at the [[2014 MTV Europe Music Awards]].

As of 2018, the single has sold 3.<!--pure sales per Billboard citation-->7 million copies in the US and has been certified sextuple [[RIAA certification|platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) in March 2016. It ultimately reached combined sales and track-equivalent streams of 9 million units worldwide,<ref name=worldwidesalesifpi/> becoming [[List of best-selling singles|one of the best-selling singles of all time]].

==Background==
Following the release of Grande's debut studio album ''[[Yours Truly (Ariana Grande album)|Yours Truly]]'' in September 2013, which was met with critical acclaim, Grande announced in October 2013 that she had already begun writing and working on her second studio album with previous producers from her debut album, including [[Harmony Samuels]], [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]], The Rascals and Tommy Brown.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande Twitter announces she's working on second album in studio|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/3392/20140113/ariana-grande-twitter-announces-shes-working-second-album-studio.htm|work=Music Times}}</ref> Grande was initially aiming at releasing the album around February 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande Starts Working on Her Second Album|url=http://www.disneydreaming.com/2013/10/31/ariana-grande-starts-working-on-her-second-album/|publisher=Disneydreaming.com|access-date=May 17, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203014804/http://www.disneydreaming.com/2013/10/31/ariana-grande-starts-working-on-her-second-album/|archive-date=December 3, 2013|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In January 2014, recording sessions for the album officially began and Grande confirmed she was working with new producers [[Ryan Tedder]], Savan Kotecha, [[Benny Blanco]] and [[Max Martin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Christina|title=Ariana Grande Talks Working With Max Martin For Second Album|url=http://www.idolator.com/7503309/ariana-grande-second-album-producers-max-martin|publisher=SpinMedia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fox|first=Sarah|title=Ariana Grande back to work in the studio, recording second album|url=http://theslanted.com/2014/01/12960/ariana-grande-back-to-work-in-the-studio-recording-second-album/|publisher=Grimm Media Publications LLC}}</ref> It was announced on March 3, 2014 that Grande would be featured on the fifth single from [[Chris Brown]]'s upcoming sixth studio album ''[[X (Chris Brown album)|X]]'' titled "Don't Be Gone Too Long".<ref>{{cite web|last=Wass|first=Mike|title=Ariana Grande's Duet With Chris Brown Is Apparently Called "Don't Be Gone Too Long"|url=http://www.idolator.com/7508177/ariana-grande-duet-chris-brown-dont-be-gone-too-long|publisher=SpinMedia}}</ref> The single was originally set for release on March 25, 2014, but it was postponed due to Brown being sent to jail awaiting trial on assault charges.<ref name=":1">{{cite web|last=Wass|first=Mike|title=Chris Brown And Ariana Grande's Duet "Don't Be Gone Too Long" Has Been Postponed|url=http://www.idolator.com/7510240/chris-brown-ariana-grande-duet-postponed|publisher=SpinMedia}}</ref> Grande announced the song's delay on March 17, 2014 via Twitter, stating "My loves... so obviously some things have changed recently... So we have to delay the dbgtl countdown, some things are out of our control".<ref name=":1" /> That same night she held a live stream to make up for the single's delay, where she previewed four new songs from her second album.<ref>{{cite web|last=Inocencio|first=Marc|title=Ariana Grande Teases Four New Songs During LiveStream: Listen|url=http://www.ryanseacrest.com/2014/03/24/ariana-grande-teases-four-news-song-during-livestream-listen/|publisher=Ryan Seacrest Productions}}</ref> Two days later, Grande revealed that due the song's delay, she would be releasing the first single from her upcoming sophomore studio album earlier instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/446445506508898304|title=Ariana Grande on Twitter: "now you'll be getting my 1st single off my new album sooner. dbgtl will come out just a little later than expected thank u for understanding"|date=March 20, 2014|accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Grande confirms Brown single is on hold|url=http://www.covermg.com/grande-confirms-brown-single-is-on-hold/|publisher=Think Agency|access-date=May 17, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518025642/http://www.covermg.com/grande-confirms-brown-single-is-on-hold/|archive-date=May 18, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

{{Quote box
| quote = "I fell in love with Iggy when I saw this video of her performing 'Work' live, and I just thought she was so original and I loved the way she pronounced her words... I thought we would make the perfect girl-power duo for 'Problem', so I'm very grateful that she did it with me."
| source = – Grande, on her collaboration with Azalea.<ref name=autogenerated14>{{cite web|last1=Murray|first1=Nick|title=Watch Ariana Grande and Iggy Azalea's 'Problem' Lyric Video – Premiere|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-ariana-grande-and-iggy-azaleas-problem-lyric-video-premiere-20140430|website=Rolling Stone|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref>
| width = 30em
| align = right
}}
Grande had met Azalea at the 2013 [[MTV Europe Music Awards]] where they had presented an award together, and hung out at [[Katy Perry]]'s after party in Amsterdam, where they expressed interest in working together.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lewis|first=Maria|title=She loves a good burger! Vegan singer Ariana Grande reveals how rapper Iggy Azalea maintains her bootylicious derriere|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2621994/Vegan-singer-Ariana-Grande-reveals-rapper-Iggy-Azalea-maintains-bootylicious-derriere.html}}</ref> They had originally planned for Azalea to appear on Grande's debut album in September 2013, however, it never panned out.<ref>{{cite web|last=Garibaldi|first=Christina|title=Ariana Grande's 'Problem' Video Is Coming: Find Out The 'Mod' Details|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1820830/iggy-azalea-ariana-grande-problem/|publisher=Viacom International Inc.}}</ref> Once Grande began working on "Problem" she thought Azalea would be the perfect fit for the track to create "the perfect girl-power duo" for the song.<ref name="autogenerated14" /><ref name="autogenerated19">{{cite web|last1=Garibaldi|first1=Christina|title=Ariana Grande's 'Problem' Video Is Coming: Find Out The 'Mod' Details|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1820830/iggy-azalea-ariana-grande-problem/|publisher=MTV|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> Azalea agreed to appear on the song and went in with producer [[Max Martin]] to write her own verse before recording it for the song.<ref name="autogenerated19" /> The line "one less problem without you" was inspired by an article from ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sharp|first1=Katie|title=You've Probably Never Heard of Savan Kotecha, but Everyone Has Heard His Music|url=http://mic.com/articles/92957/you-ve-probably-never-heard-of-savan-kotecha-but-everyone-has-heard-his-music|website=Music.Mic|accessdate=June 28, 2015|date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> [[Big Sean]], who is featured in Grande's previous single "[[Right There (Ariana Grande song)|Right There]]", also appears on the song uncredited as a background vocalist in which he provides the whisper-like vocals of the chorus although he is not a featured artist.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|title=Ariana Grande talks 'Problem' & Second album, Due Out August/September|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6070079/ariana-grande-talks-problem-single-second-album-due-out|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> Initially while recording songs for the album, after Grande had recorded "Problem" she "fell out of love" with the song and didn't want it to appear on her second album.<ref name="autogenerated9">{{cite web|last1=Lipshutz|first1=Jason|title=Ariana Grande's Huge 'Problem': Inside The Monster Hot 100 Debut|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6084803/ariana-grande-problem-hot-100-debut-iggy-azalea-interview|website=Billboard|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> However, following an album listening session with her management and record label, when "Problem" came on Grande said "What the hell is wrong with me? Holy shit!", realizing her love for the song and decided to keep it for the album.<ref name="autogenerated9" /> Lyrically, the song is about "the feeling of being absolutely terrified to re-approach a relationship that's gone sour – but you want to more than anything."<ref name="Lyrics explain">{{cite web|last1=Lipshutz|first1=Jason|title=Ariana Grande Talks 'Problem' Single & Second Album, Due Out August/September|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6070079/ariana-grande-talks-problem-single-second-album-due-out|website=Billboard|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref>

==Release and remixes==
After recording multiple songs for the album, Grande stated that she had chosen the first single from her album.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mensah|first=Esi|title=Ariana Grande Has Chosen Her Next Single, But Keeps Fans in Suspense After Releasing Video Tease!|url=http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/145774/Ariana-Grande-Has-Chosen-Her-Next-Single-But-Keeps-Fans-In-Suspense-After-Releasing-Video-Tease|publisher=GiantDigital|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518071253/http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/145774/Ariana-Grande-Has-Chosen-Her-Next-Single-But-Keeps-Fans-In-Suspense-After-Releasing-Video-Tease|archivedate=May 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name="autogenerated6">{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande Announces New Single 'Problem'|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/04/15/ariana-grande-announces-new-single-problem/|publisher=Rap-Up.com}}</ref> On April 15, 2014, it was officially announced that "Problem" would be the title of the lead single from the album.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wass|first=Mike|title=Ariana Grande Poses Seductively on the Back of a Motorcycle. Just Because.|url=http://www.idolator.com/7513343/ariana-grande-sexy-motorbike-shoot|publisher=SpinMedia}}</ref> Grande later hinted that Australian rapper [[Iggy Azalea]] would accompany her on the track.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Garibaldi|first1=Christina|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1726251/ariana-grande-problem-new-single/|title=Ariana Grande Reveals Problematic Single Title, Hints At Iggy Azalea Collabo - MTV|date=April 16, 2014|accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> She created online buzz in the weeks leading up to her single's release through social media, first released promotional images from the single's photo shoot all throughout March 2014.<ref name="autogenerated5">{{cite web|last1=Wass|first1=Mike|title=Ariana Grande Poses Seductively on the Back of a Motorcycle. Just Because.|url=http://www.idolator.com/7513343/ariana-grande-sexy-motorbike-shoot|website=Idolator|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> On April 10, 2014, Grande asked her fans to choose between two new possible images to be used for the single's artwork release.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Emily|title=Ariana Grande's Next Single Cover Is Up To You: Vote Now|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1725897/ariana-grande-single-cover-vote.jhtml|publisher=MTV|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> After the votes were tallied, she revealed the winning cover artwork through her [[Instagram]] account the next day with the hashtag #10daystilproblem, and revealed that [[Iggy Azalea]] would be assisting her on the track.<ref>{{cite web|title=SINGLE COVER: ARIANA GRANDE F/ IGGY AZALEA – 'PROBLEM'|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/04/17/single-cover-ariana-grande-f-iggy-azalea-problem/|website=Rap-Up|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> The winning image, the more seductive image of the pair, shows Grande leaning back in a foldout chair, dressed in a black camisole, white thigh-highs, and metal-tipped stilettos. Grande is also shown flipping through her hair while looking directly into the camera.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bobb|first1=Maurice|title=Ariana Grande Teams With Iggy Azalea For 'Problems': See The Cover Art|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1726389/ariana-grande-teams-with-iggy-azalea-problems-see-cover-art.jhtml|publisher=MTV|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> The song was released at midnight to iTunes on April 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gil|first1=Kassandra Vanessa|title=Ariana Grande Announces Her New Single "Problem" Feat Iggy Azalea!|url=http://www.popstoptv.com/entertainment-411/ariana-grande-announces-new-single-problem-feat-iggy-azalea-34808.html|website=POPSTOP TV|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> The single was made available for pre-order on <!-- Source states and was published on April 21. -->April 21, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande's "Problem" Available For Pre-Order on iTunes|url=http://www.disneydreaming.com/2014/04/21/ariana-grandes-problem-available-for-pre-order-on-itunes/|website=Disney Daydreaming|accessdate=June 14, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224113501/http://www.disneydreaming.com/2014/04/21/ariana-grandes-problem-available-for-pre-order-on-itunes/|archivedate=December 24, 2014}}</ref> The single made its world radio premiere on ''[[On Air with Ryan Seacrest]]'' on April 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perricone|first1=Kathleen|title=Ariana Grande Talks 'Problem' and Future of Her Chris Brown Duet|url=http://www.ryanseacrest.com/2014/04/28/ariana-grande-talks-problem-and-future-of-her-chris-brown-duet/|publisher=RyanSeacrest.com|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> A remix of the song was released on May 16, 2014 entitled the "Young California Remix" and features an additional rap verse from American rapper [[Problem (rapper)|Problem]].<ref name="autogenerated15">{{cite web|title=NEW MUSIC: ARIANA GRANDE F/ PROBLEM & IGGY AZALEA – 'PROBLEM (REMIX)'|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/05/16/new-music-ariana-grande-f-problem-iggy-azalea-problem-remix/|website=Rap-Up|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Garner|first1=Matthew|title=#YoungCalifornia Remix: Ariana Grande "Problem" feat. Problem & Iggy Azalea|url=http://www.youngcalifornia.com/2014/05/youngcalifornia-remix-ariana-grande-problem-feat-problem-iggy-azalea/|publisher=YoungCalifornia.com|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> A Spanglish version of the song was also released featuring Colombian rapper [[J Balvin]] for the Hispanophone market, making it the second collaboration between the two artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=¡Ariana Grande cantará en español la canción 'Problem'!|url=http://www2.esmas.com/entretenimiento/musica/noticias/748518/ariana-grande-cantara-espanol-cancion-problem/|publisher=[[Esmas.com]]|accessdate=August 5, 2014|language=Spanish|date=July 31, 2014}}</ref> In August 11, a remix version by DJ Boss in Drama was released in Brazil featuring Brazilian [[pop music|pop]] singer [[Gretchen (singer)|Gretchen]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Boss in Drama remixa "Problem" de Ariana Grande com participação de Gretchen|url=http://www.papelpop.com/2014/08/boss-in-drama-junta-ariana-grande-e-iggy-azalea-com-gretchen-em-remix-de-problem/|website=Papel Pop|accessdate=August 5, 2014|language=Portuguese|date=July 31, 2014}}</ref>

==Composition==
Musically, "Problem" is an uptempo [[dance-pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song<ref name="Huff">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/28/ariana-grande-problem_n_5226140.html |title=Ariana Grande Drops New Single 'Problem' Featuring Iggy Azalea |first=Ryan |last=Kristobak |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=April 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=summer>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/how-ariana-grande-and-max-martin-made-problem-the-song-of-the-summer-20140522|date=2014-05-22|first=Andy|last=Greene|title=How Ariana Grande and Max Martin Made 'Problem' the Song of the Summer|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=2018-11-27|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name="idolator" /><ref name="autogenerated2">{{cite web|last1=Wass|first1=Mike|title=Ariana Grande Debuts "Problem" With Sexy Radio Disney Music Awards Performance: Watch|url=http://www.idolator.com/7515862/ariana-grande-problem-performance-radio-disney-music-awards|website=Idolator|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> that incorporates elements of [[jazz]], [[Contemporary R&B#1990s|contemporary '90s R&B]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[funk]]<ref name="autogenerated2" /><ref name="autogenerated3">{{cite web|title=Review: Ariana Grande's hot new single 'Problem' is problem-free anthem for the summer [LISTEN]|url=http://www.musictimes.com/articles/5770/20140428/review-ariana-grandes-hot-new-single-problem-free-anthem-summer.htm|publisher=MusicTimes.com|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> which comprises the instruments like [[drums]], [[saxophone]]s and [[trumpets]].<ref name="autogenerated2" /> It runs for a duration of three minutes and 14 seconds. The song was written by Grande, Azalea, Savan Kotecha, Ilya Salmanzadeh and [[Max Martin]], and produced by the latter two along with [[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shellback on Maratone |url=http://maratone.se/producers/Shellback |website=Maratone |accessdate=June 14, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505020637/http://maratone.se/producers/Shellback |archivedate=May 5, 2014 }}</ref><ref name="aus"/> According to the sheet music published by [[Alfred Publishing|Alfred Publishing Co., Inc]]. on Musicnotes.com, "Problem" is composed in the key of [[G-sharp minor|G{{music|sharp}} minor]] and set in [[common time]] at a moderate [[tempo]] of 103 [[beats per minute]]. The melody spans the tonal range of G{{music|sharp}}<sub>3</sub> to G{{music|sharp}}<sub>5</sub> belt and E{{music|flat}}<sub>6</sub> in falsetto, while the music follows the [[chord progression]] of Emaj<sub>7</sub>–F{{music|sharp}}–B– Emaj<sub>7</sub>–F{{music|sharp}}–G♯m.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ariana Grande "Problem" Sheet Music|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdFPE.asp?ppn=MN0134912&|publisher=Musicnotes, Inc.}}</ref>

{{listen
 | pos          = left
 | filename     = Ariana Grande - Problem.ogg
 | title        = "Problem"
 | description  = A 19-second sample of "Problem", an uptempo [[dance-pop]] song with influences of R&B subgenres that lyrically, revolves around an on again off again relationship.
 | format       = [[Ogg]]
}}

The track opens with a dose of "jazzy saxophones" before the more modern "horn-heavy" "drum-filled beat drops".<ref name="autogenerated3" /><ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|last1=James|first1=Nicolas|title=Ariana Grande – Problem Feat. Iggy Azalea|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/ariana-grande-problem-feat-iggy-azalea-new-song.1884030.html|publisher=HotNewHipHop.com|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name="autogenerated7">{{cite web|last1=Benjamin|first1=Jeff|title=HEAR ARIANA GRANDE & IGGY AZALEA'S SEXY, SAX-SATURATED "PROBLEM"|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2014/04/ariana-grande-problem-iggy-azalea|website=fuseTV|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name="autogenerated4">{{cite web|last=Ornos |first=Riza |title=Ariana Grande's 'Problem,' Five Things You Need to Know |url=http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/549719/20140428/ariana-grande-problem-full-lyrics-2014-radio.htm |publisher=International Business Times AU. |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140430040002/http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/549719/20140428/ariana-grande-problem-full-lyrics-2014-radio.htm |archivedate=April 30, 2014 }}</ref> The song's melody constantly builds toward something that "should be explosive", before Azalea brings it back down with her verse "Smart money bettin' I'll be better off without you/ In no time I'll be forgettin' all about you/ You sayin' that you know but I really, really doubt you/understand my life is easy when I ain't around you."<ref name="autogenerated3" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Linder|first=Emilee|title=Ariana Grande's 'Problem' Is Perfect For Ditching That Bad Boy in Your Life|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1816779/ariana-grandes-problem-is-perfect-for-ditching-that-bad-boy-in-your-life/|publisher=Viacom International Inc.}}</ref> Azalea also makes a reference to the [[Jay-Z]] song "[[99 Problems]]" at the end of her verse "There's a million yous baby boo, so don't be dumb/ I got 99 problems but you won't be one." Additionally, Grande's notes serve as a [[metaphor]] for what the song is about.<ref name="autogenerated4"/> She can't get rid of her crush, who she knows isn't good for her and can't help but fall in love quickly. As her "heart gets lighter and lighter", Grande sings "Head in the clouds/ got no weight on my shoulders/ I should be wiser and realize that I've got/ One less problem without you."<ref name="autogenerated2" /><ref name="autogenerated1" /><ref name="autogenerated4" /> A writer from ''[[Rap-Up]]'' describes the track as an "infectious horn-heavy jam" which features a "carefree" Ariana "declaring her independence" which also includes "an empowering verse from Iggy Azalea and a whispering Big Sean on the hook."<ref name="Rap Up">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/04/27/new-music-ariana-grande-f-iggy-azalea-problem/ |title=New Music: Ariana Grande f/ Iggy Azalea – 'Problem' |publisher=''Rap-Up''. SpinMedia |date=April 27, 2014 |accessdate=April 27, 2014}}</ref> Several critics noted a similarity between the [[jazz]]y [[saxophone]] breakdown in "Problem" and [[Jason Derulo]]'s 2013 single "[[Talk Dirty (Jason Derulo song)|Talk Dirty]]."<ref name="autogenerated7" />

==Critical reception==
[[File:Iggy Azalea - ACL Music Festival (5).jpg|thumb|upright|Iggy Azalea contributed a verse to "Problem"]]
Mike Wass of [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] described the song as "an odd blend of [[1990s in music#Pop|'90s pop]] and current urban trends but there's no denying that it's catchy."<ref name="idolator" /> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called the song a "dramatic reinvention," and also notes, "The idea that Grande was collaborating with bad girl du jour Iggy Azalea prompted all kinds of speculation, and the result is more or less what everybody expected: Grande's enviable pipes are still the centerpiece, but she also invites a sax-drunk loop, sexy whisper tracks, and Azalea's Jay Z-referencing high-speed verse to the party as well."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Kyle|title=Ariana Grande teams up with Iggy Azalea for new single 'Problem'|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2014/04/28/ariana-grande-new-single-problem-iggy-azalea/|website=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> ''Music Times'' commented that "the saxophone-filled track continues the pattern set by Grande's 2013 debut album ''Yours Truly'' by being heavily influenced by the '90s R&B scene. This time, 'Problem' pulls from the funky, funky streets with a jazz-influenced riff. An overwhelming (but welcome) dose of saxophone leads the song before the more modern drum-filled beat drops."<ref name="autogenerated3" /> In addition, [[4Music]] said "Ariana's sweet-sounding vocals contrast brilliantly with Problem's sexy sax and Iggy's gritty rap."<ref name="4music">{{cite episode|series=This Week's Fresh Music Top 20|title=This Week's Fresh Music Top 20|airdate=July 25, 2014|network=[[4Music]]}}</ref>

Pitchfork named it "Best New Track", saying that it "bears all the hallmarks of a future smash, as if the future wasn't actually right now."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goble|first1=Corban|title=Ariana Grande: 'Problem' [ft. Iggy Azalea]|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/16899-ariana-grande-problem-ft-iggy-azalea/|website=Pitchfork Media|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> Writing for [[MTV]], Emilee Lindner praised the song's throwback sound, which Grande admits to striving for, while still keeping it fresh and modern, stating: "The song is so excitingly new but also decidedly so retro... The cranky sax, the whispered chorus, the airy harmonies and Iggy's snarky feature all tied in with a juicy modern beat." Lindner continued by calling it "the freshest pop song of the moment", commending the song's production for its "more than a few unexpected throwbacks", comparing the [[saxophone]] loops to [[Jennifer Lopez]]'s 2004 single "[[Get Right (song)|Get Right]]" saying "It's the same notes over and over, but its attitude doesn't let you zone out", while the whispers in the chorus echoes to the [[Ying Yang Twins]]' 2005 single "[[Wait (The Whisper Song)|Wait]]."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Linder|first1=Emilee|title=Ariana Grande's 'Problem' Has More Than A Few Unexpected Throwbacks|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1817447/ariana-grandes-problem-5-unexpected-throwbacks-in-her-new-track/|publisher=MTV|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' listed the song as one of the "10 Best Songs of 2014 (so far)" saying that "the snappy R&B of Ariana Grande's breakout hit '[[The Way (Ariana Grande song)|The Way]]' feels minimalist compared to the multi-faceted bubblegum of 'Problem'".<ref>{{cite web|title=10 Best Songs of 2014 (So Far): Critics' Picks|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/6150405/10-best-songs-of-2014-so-far-critics-picks|date=July 10, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2014}}</ref> Meanwhile, Pitchfork named it the 33rd best song of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/9555-the-100-best-tracks-of-2014/7/|title=The 100 Best Tracks of 2014|work=Pitchfork Media}}</ref>

